  "description": [
    "THE BROWNING CHIEF John E Davies Editor and Owner A weekly newspaper published every Friday at Browning Glacier County Montana Entered as 2nd class matter July IS 1931 at the postoffice at Browning Montana under act at March 3 1879 Subscription 200 year in advance LAPSE IN LEADERSHIP As the Korean truce talks plod steadily toward a stalemate it be comes more than ever import ant that the American govern ment make its purposes clear to the American people Washing ton may not be aware of how confused and frustrated millions of people feel But a breakdown of negotiations could easily bring the United States closer to an all out war on China than it has yet been This danger would be accentu ated should the Chinese Reds proceed with the major attack in IndoChina which has been threatened increasingly in recent weeks If it appeared that the Communists might break through that principal barrier to south east Asia what would the United States do beyond supplying the French as it is today Send in troops It is more likely that public opinion would demand blows aimed at China itself Some 5000 enemy casualties in Korea last week measure a"
  ],
